+# Solution for EF1003: Detect string.Format and string.Concat calls
+
+## Root Cause
+
+The `StringsUsageInRawQueriesDiagnosticAnalyzer` (EF1003) only detected two kinds of dangerous SQL string construction:
+1. Interpolated strings (`$"...{variable}..."`)
+2. Binary `+` string concatenation (`"..." + variable`)
+
+Explicit calls to `string.Concat(...)` and `string.Format(...)` that incorporate non-constant values were not detected, leaving a gap where developers could inadvertently introduce SQL injection vulnerabilities.
+
+## Change Description
+
+In `AnalyzeInvocation`, a third case was added to the switch expression that matches any `IInvocationOperation` whose target method is named `"Concat"` or `"Format"` on the `System.String` type. A new helper method `AnalyzeStringMethodCall` was introduced to walk the arguments of the call:
+
+- For arguments that are array creation expressions (i.e., the compiler-generated `params object[]` or `params string[]` array), each element is individually checked for a constant value.
+- For all other arguments, a missing constant value triggers the warning.
+
+If any non-constant argument is found the method returns `true` and the existing `StringConcatenationDescriptor` (EF1003) is reported — the same diagnostic already used for `+` concatenation.
+
+Constant-only calls such as `string.Concat("A", "B")` or `string.Format("SQL {0}", "constant")` are left unreported, consistent with how constant `+` concatenation is handled.
+
+## Files Edited
+
+- `src/EFCore.Analyzers/StringsUsageInRawQueriesDiagnosticAnalyzer.cs` — added the `string.Concat`/`string.Format` detection arm in `AnalyzeInvocation` and the `AnalyzeStringMethodCall` helper method.
+- `test/EFCore.Analyzers.Tests/StringConcatenationInRawQueriesAnalyzerTests.cs` — added four new theory tests covering constant/non-constant `string.Concat` and `string.Format` calls.
